Good day, dear journalists, here at the Tallinn presentation and press center, with all interested parties watching us through the live stream.
It is the sixteenth of December.
The Tallinn City Government has held its regular session, and today, at the city government's press conference, we have before you the Mayor of the city, Mihhail Kõlvart, the Director of Communications from the first of January, two thousand twenty-one, Kirsti Ruul, our good acquaintance from the Health Board's Department of Epidemic Control, Irina Dontšenko, and the Head of Direct Assistance at the Estonian Animal Protection Society, Kaisa Kamm.
And today, we have already heard and read the news that there have been an additional five hundred and ninety coronavirus positive cases in the past twenty-four hours, which is why Irina Dontšenko from the Health Board's Department of Epidemic Control will also start today.
Good day from the Health Board.
Indeed, today's number is five hundred and ninety, what does that mean for us?
It means that the intensity of infections is still very high throughout Estonia.
And if we take these five hundred and ninety cases out of the total number of tests conducted, these cases make up ten percent, and the highest number of cases were registered in Harju County, sixty percent, in Ida-Viru County fourteen percent, and in Tartu County eight percent.
The incidence rate per one hundred thousand inhabitants in the last fourteen days is four hundred and seventy point sixty-six today, and it is still the highest.
If we look at the counties, it is the highest in Ida-Viru County, one thousand fifty-three, in Harju County five hundred fifty-eight, in Rapla County three hundred seventy-eight, in Hiiumaa three hundred eleven, in Võru County three hundred seven, and in Tartu County three hundred.
This is the so-called top five-six.
What continues to be very concerning for us is the readiness and capability of our hospital system, and in this regard, it must be said that as of today, there are three hundred and fourteen patients receiving hospital treatment, of whom twenty-eight require serious, or intensive care, and among them, sixteen are on ventilators. Unfortunately, three people have passed away in the last twenty-four hours.

Let's summarize the previous, the previous fiftieth week a little bit.
A total of three thousand one hundred and sixty-two cases were added, which has increased by eight point two percent compared to the previous week in absolute numbers.
Here it can be added that when we look at testing, almost one, almost twelve percent of these positive tests are so-called tenth-day tests, meaning that when close contacts can take a test on the tenth day, we can identify and detect another relatively large number of cases, which is very positive.
And the number of infections is still on the rise in ten counties, primarily in Harju County, Jõgeva County, Järva County, Lääne-Viru County, Ida-Viru County, Pärnu County, and Rapla County.
Currently, we see a trend where the infection rate is starting to decrease from the north towards the south, meaning that it is moving from Ida-Viru County towards Tartu County, towards Võru County, which actually creates a more attentive attitude towards these counties as well.
Regarding the places of infection, there hasn't been any significant change in patterns. People are more likely to get infected within their families, at work, and there are also other places of infection, which led to certain restrictions and limitations imposed by the Government of the Republic.
We are still concerned about the number of cases where we do not know the source of infection.
Last week, this number was thirty-four percent, which again indicates that we still have a high risk of infection and the disease can be contracted from anywhere.
We continue to register imported cases, but fortunately, the number has been decreasing over the weeks, and last week there were sixty-one of them.
And most of these cases come from Russia, Finland-Sweden, and Sweden.
Age structure.
As the number of cases is increasing rapidly, there are new cases in all age groups.
Mostly, there was an increase in the age group of sixty to sixty-nine.
There were seventeen percent of them, fifty to fifty-nine thirteen percent, and forty to forty-nine twelve percent.
The positive aspect is that the number of cases in the age group of ninety plus decreased by a quarter last week.
We know that Covid can be asymptomatic or with symptoms, so last week, ten percent of the cases were asymptomatic.
And one hundred and eighty-seven people required hospitalization.
It is very important to note that nearly eighty percent of those hospitalized were sixty plus, which indicates that the disease is worsening and the course of the disease will be more serious in older people.
We still have concerns about care facilities, which are the most vulnerable risk areas, and we conducted a small analysis comparing the fourteen-day incidence per one hundred thousand inhabitants in nursing homes and among the general population. Among the sixty plus clients in nursing homes, the risk of infection is almost seven times higher.
Again, if the disease enters nursing homes, it is a serious problem.
And of course, we continue to emphasize that our healthcare system is currently under a very heavy burden.
And we must do everything to ensure that all people who need hospital treatment, not only Covid patients but also those with other concerns, can receive the necessary care.
A few words about the incidence in Harju County.
As of today, the fourteen-day incidence per one hundred thousand inhabitants is five hundred and eighty-eight point eighty-two.
The number for Tallinn is nine hundred, for Loksa one thousand three hundred and thirty-eight, and for Maardu seven hundred and fifty-one.
But let's compare it again with Ida-Viru County, where this figure is one thousand fifty-three, so Ida-Viru County is still the biggest concern for us.
In Harju County, there are currently nearly seventeen thousand people under active monitoring, of which fourteen thousand are close contacts and over three thousand are active cases. Today, we have twenty-four active outbreaks, mostly in workplaces, family clusters, but also in nursing homes.
And now, what should we do next, how should we behave?
Figuratively speaking, in order to overcome this crisis, everything is very, very simple and clear.
Everyone who is sick must calmly endure the illness at home, and during the time when they are infectious, all their contacts should be minimized.
That way, we can get rid of the virus.
Well, that's an ideal world that we are moving towards.
But surely, we probably cannot achieve it one hundred percent.
But still, we must all contribute together now, in order not to spread the virus and to help those who need assistance.
And what do we still need to do? We must adhere to the measures imposed by the government, maintain distance, wear masks, reduce contacts, avoid crowded places and events, and cancel large parties this time.
And we must spend Christmas mostly at home and in a small circle of family members and those with whom we interact daily, and stay at home as much as possible and enjoy the beautiful Estonian nature, in order to reduce the risk of getting infected ourselves and not transmit the infection to anyone in the family.
I wish everyone a merry Christmas spirit and let's stay healthy, thank you!
Thank you, Dr. Irina Dontšenko and the perspective of Tallinn Mayor Mihhail Kõlvart on the coronavirus.
