Christmas and the end of the year are approaching with unstoppable force, and there will be fireworks at the end of the year and other suitable activities. And today we have words of caution from both the mayor and a representative of the Animal Protection Society. Mayor Mihhail Kõlvart.

Yes, one symbol of New Year's Eve is traditionally fireworks. The city has organized it every year, and this year it may have a special meaning. Firstly, well, we all need positive emotions, which have been lacking a lot lately. And the city has been trying to provide this emotion in the urban space. However, we must take into account the current epidemiological situation. Therefore, of course, such a traditional event will not take place in Freedom Square. And we want to disperse people. So the fireworks will take place in different locations this year, in different districts, almost in every district, except Nõmme and Kristiine. Six locations have been selected for the fireworks. And once again, we appeal to the residents of the city that if we want these events to take place, if we want the city-organized fireworks to take place, then it is necessary to keep a distance and also wear a mask. However, the locations have been chosen in such a way that this opportunity exists. But we have one more very important appeal to the residents of Tallinn. We are organizing fireworks centrally in different locations, hoping that people will not start organizing it privately, buying fireworks, and shooting them off. Because it is a problem for both people and animals.
And this is an annual problem and we need to understand that it is not environmentally friendly either.
And we really hope that this understanding will arise among our people this year.
That there are specialists who can do it professionally and that is why we do it, but all private fireworks should be eliminated, as we try to protect each other, but also our smaller friends, and I would gladly give the floor to a representative of the Animal Protection Society.
Thank you, Mr. Mayor.
Yes, we have the direct assistance manager of the Estonian Animal Protection Society, Kaisa Kamm, participating in the press conference, so a joyful New Year's Eve is a little worrisome for you.
Please.
Greetings also from the Estonian Animal Protection Society.
And firstly, I am very pleased that as the years go by, more and more is being said about the negative impact of fireworks on both animals and the environment.
At this point, I would also like to thank Tallinn for organizing such a fireworks display in a safe environment, and I hope that this will not be just a one-year initiative and that other cities and municipalities will follow suit.
The reason why these fireworks cause so much concern for the Estonian Animal Protection Society is multifaceted.
Firstly, it is not only a concern for our domestic animals, such as dogs and cats, but also for urban animals in general, including horses and birds.
But I think I would first like to talk about the animals in our homes.
Fireworks cause a lot of distress for them because they are loud and create irrational fear in dogs.
They don't know how to behave, they start running away, they freeze, and I believe that if someone manages to study the statistics of the Tallinn Animal Shelter, they will find that there are a lot of stray dogs, which can cause accidents.
Plus, it simply causes worry.
In addition to that, there are also our urban birds.
They either fly very far away and can't make it back, or their food supplies run out.
So we are causing a lot of suffering to them for no reason at all.
So it would be very good if you would simply go to places that are controlled, we know where they are happening.
Pet owners can monitor where these fireworks are taking place themselves, and we don't have to worry about indiscriminate fireworks being set off when they take their dog outside.
This is one of our main concerns.
Thank you!
And perhaps from this side, we can still add and ask that if it is at all possible, parents also keep an eye on their little ones and that it is not necessary to set off their own, self-made fireworks on Christmas Eve and on the first day of Christmas.
So maybe we could somehow get rid of this tradition as well.
But here, parental care and guidance are probably needed to determine what is appropriate and what is not.
But thank you in any case, Kaisa Kamm, the direct assistance manager of the Estonian Animal Protection Society.
